snippet.textDisplay:
2 years ago I had a guinea pig. He loved me and I cared about him. He had gotten sick the year before, but he got better. Anyways, that year he started loosing weight. He went from 2.5 lbs to 1 lb. I was super worried about him. We took him to the vet and found out he had kidney stones. About 1-2 months later, he died while I was at school. When I got home, I didn’t know. My dad wanted to tell me something and I asked if I could get my guinea pig, I was confused when he said I couldn’t. He told me that my guinea pig had died while I was at school. That was the worst sad thing I’ve had.

Another story. Last year in choir class I had a solo. We were singing some nights and I had the pre-chorus part. We sang along with recording for a backup part. We started early, and were off tempo enough that it was obvious. I had the first solo. No one was angry at me because somehow I managed to get everyone back on tempo, but I sounded like I got stage fright. After that, we watched the recording in class, and that was just as bad, if not worse.

snippet.textDisplay: When I was younger, my family had a pet cat named Bubba.  He was a very old cat, I believe he had a heart monitor infact, he looked and acted like a grandpa most the time.  I knew we would have to put him down someday, my parents told us that.  I was extremely attached to Bubba, I grew up with him.  One day I went to my best friends house, an spent the day with her, maybe even slept over.  When I got back the next day, I came home and not long after I entered the house, my mom warned me.  She said that Bubba wasn't around anymore, and that while I was at my friends house, they took him to the vet and put him down.  I didn't know how to feel in that moment, I knew it was better that he moved on, his heart monitor was failing and he looked uncomfortable most days.  But in that moment all I could think was "I never got to say goodbye to him."  It sounds so silly, but to this day I cry whenever I think about him.

snippet.textDisplay:
Guys, you should know that mourning could take over a year, so you feeling things about your loved ones passing a year after is completely normal and you should know that

-

I have a story of my own with the death of a loved one to share

So i'm 17...
When I was 8 years old, my grandfather died december 23rd (that's like a week over 9 years ago) and I was So devastated the day i got told but the worst part about his death is that I felt so incredibly guilty because I never really liked spending time with him. I found him weird and he was always like peeing and doing his business on himself; basically I just didn't understand the concept of Alzheimer's, let alone comprehend it so now every time i think back to it for too long I breakdown crying. I used to not be by his side and look at him weirdly when i was at my grandma's house, seeing my cousin (6months younger) treat him so nicely and just looking back at that was Horrible. It took me a long time to admit that was the one thing that actually triggered my depression and i've been dealing with that along side anxiety ever since. Not like ADHD was going to come all by itself but you know.

And again, this was 9 years ago, i now have a better understanding or mental illnesses and disorders (because I have ADHD, the topic is just very close to heart) but it was and is still so heartbreaking.

Last night I had a lucid dream where I was playing with him and it was so beautiful even though I knew that it was a dream and I would wake up.

snippet.textDisplay: Just a few years back I lost my aunt to manslaughter. I was at my friends during the time, and my cousin Remy was spamming my phone at 7 in the morning.(he lives in Florida, us in Ohio) and on about the 3rd call did I finally realize my phone was going off. I answered tired and confused sense we stayed up til about 4-5 AM, and even though he is always calm and always has a calm voice, I could hear the panic in his voice. He automatically said "where's your dad? I need to talk to your dad, its important!" And I was like "I'm not home, but my dads probably asleep and definitely isn't going to answer his phone. The best I can tell you is to call my mom and get my dad, here's her number." And we basically hung up after that. A bit concerned, but I was tired and fell back asleep. My mom picked me up about 4, and I asked what had happened (I had almost completely forgot). She said my aunt had been punched and was in the ICU. I called my cousin Hannah, and explained what had happened. She asked her dad and her dad was like yea, she was hurt, she's in the ICU, but he didn't want to tell her just yet.  The hospital said she was brain dead, and thinking about pulling the plug. I had no reaction. I walked upstairs then came back down another half hour later and was like "did they make a decision? Did they do it?" And my mom was like "they probably already did." I didn't realize what had happened until that night. Started crying at 10, and couldn't calm down til 3 AM. It hit 4 am when i had fallen back asleep. I had school the next day, but didn't go. I felt so shitty because I felt like my reaction wasn't enough. Like I didn't care, like I never loved her. But I did. I still do. (For anyone curious, someone was groping her breasts, and the bartender kicked him out. He tried to come back, but she held her ground. He punched her, right at the entrance to the bar, and that has caused her to fall down, and crack her skull starting from the top of her head, all the way down to where her neck would start.)

snippet.textDisplay:
When Ethan's backflip video was playing, I could really feel Ethan's pain.

On a side note, a really bad/funny part of my highschool experience was that I was a singer.

Being a singer, I had to sing the Australian National Anthem on stage in front of the school, multiple times throughout the year.

I was singing a harmony part (alto) into a microphone in front of over 2000 students.

Alto harmony unlike the main melody, was very distinguished from the melody, so the next part was very noticeable.

Mid anthem, I sung the wrong words. The wrong words to my own country's national anthem...

I even had a voice crack at this part. I'm a female. We don't have voice boxes. We can't have voice cracks. But I did.

Following this, I laughed into the microphone.

Everyone laughed at me.

The worse thing wasn't that I messed it up, or laughed, but the principal scolded all +2000 students for laughing due to my mistake and put everyone on detention for lunch.

snippet.textDisplay:
When Ethan said "They say, sticks and stones may break my bones, but words will never hurt me," specifically in the contest of that statement, it reminded me of my middle school assistant principal (I think her name was Mrs. Allen, and God Bless Her), who acknowledged that words really do hurt.


You see, I was not a particularly obedient child in my youth, and would often get into fights about what I perceived as violations against my values (generally, I was protecting my friends, or stopping something I perceived as bullying). Mrs. Allen was such a kind soul, so even when I would be called to the office, when I heard she would be the one meeting me, I breathed a sigh of relief, knowing that she would understand that, while my actions may have been rash, I had only the best of intentions, for only the best of friends.


GOOD GOD, it felt good to say that! She was AWESOME! Anyone else from McAuliffe Middle School around 2008-11 (-ish), I invite you to chime in on this, unless you hated her, in which case, I WILL FIGHT YOU TO THE DEATH!!!


Anyway, to anyone who actually read all this, thanks for indulging me! I hope you had as great of a middle school assistant principal as I did!
